The Collections.reverse() method in Java is used to reverse the order of elements in a List. It is part of the java.util.Collections class and modifies the original list directly.
‚Ä¢ Reverses the order of elements in a given List.
‚Ä¢ Works in-place, meaning it updates the original list instead of creating a new one.
‚Ä¢ Commonly used for changing display or processing order of data.

Example: Reversing an ArrayList
import java.util.*;
‚Äã
// Main class
public class GFG {
‚Äã
    // main driver method
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        // Let us create a list of strings
        List<String> mylist = new ArrayList<String>();
‚Äã
        // Adding elements to the List
        // Custom input elements
        mylist.add("practice");
        mylist.add("code");
        mylist.add("quiz");
        mylist.add("geeksforgeeks");
‚Äã
        // Print all elements originally
        System.out.println("Original List : " + mylist);
‚Äã
        // Using reverse() method to
        // reverse the element order of mylist
        Collections.reverse(mylist);
‚Äã
        // Print all elements of list in reverse order
        // using reverse() method
        System.out.println("Modified List: " + mylist);
    }
}

Output
Original List : [practice, code, quiz, geeksforgeeks]
Modified List: [geeksforgeeks, quiz, code, practice]

Syntax
  Collections.reverse(List<?> list)

How it Works
‚Ä¢ It takes a List as input.
‚Ä¢ Reverses the order of elements inside the same list.
‚Ä¢ Does not return a new list; it updates the existing one.

